WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.199
Open Settings, and look at the left rail.

p02
00:00:02.963 --> 00:00:07.509
Four pages control who gets into Wash Central and what they can do once they're in.

p03
00:00:08.418 --> 00:00:11.086
Three of them sit together under Users and Security.

p04
00:00:11.716 --> 00:00:15.333
The fourth is filed somewhere you wouldn't guess, and we'll go find it.

p05
00:00:15.821 --> 00:00:17.240
Open System Users.

p06
00:00:17.722 --> 00:00:20.408
This is the master list of everyone with an account.

p07
00:00:20.712 --> 00:00:23.132
Eight columns, and four carry the support work:

p08
00:00:23.616 --> 00:00:24.724
is the account active, does it use single sign-on,

p09
00:00:25.263 --> 00:00:26.719
when did it last sign in, and what role does it hold.

p10
00:00:27.165 --> 00:00:34.204
Email and phone are there to reach the person, not to fix the ticket.

p11
00:00:34.662 --> 00:00:36.026
Read those four in order.

p12
00:00:36.778 --> 00:00:39.024
Active tells you the account is switched on.

p13
00:00:39.669 --> 00:00:44.039
S-S-O tells you the password lives with the identity provider, not here.

p14
00:00:44.807 --> 00:00:47.176
Last Login tells you when they last got in,

p15
00:00:47.528 --> 00:00:50.351
and a blank there means the account has never been used.

p16
00:00:51.341 --> 00:00:54.372
User Level is the thread you pull into the next two pages.

p17
00:00:54.824 --> 00:00:56.630
You won't scroll this list.

p18
00:00:56.630 --> 00:00:59.160
Search by name, code, or email instead.

p19
00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:04.510
On the July eighth verified pass the tenant carried more than eight thousand accounts,

p20
00:01:04.510 --> 00:01:07.730
integration logins and the Micrologic support account included.

p21
00:01:07.730 --> 00:01:10.615
The search box earns its keep here.

p22
00:01:11.071 --> 00:01:13.711
Now the page that hides.

p23
00:01:13.711 --> 00:01:19.646
User Levels controls how long a session lasts, so you'd expect it under Users and Security.

p24
00:01:19.646 --> 00:01:20.334
It isn't.

p25
00:01:20.334 --> 00:01:24.065
It's filed under Automation, a few groups down the rail.

p26
00:01:24.065 --> 00:01:28.534
Open it there, and remember the spot, because every surprise-logout ticket ends here.

p27
00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:30.304
Three columns here.

p28
00:01:30.944 --> 00:01:31.527
A name, a security level number, and a session timeout in minutes.

p29
00:01:31.905 --> 00:01:35.426
Hold onto that number, it drives refunds on the next page.

p30
00:01:36.028 --> 00:01:43.163
The minutes are the answer for anyone who keeps getting kicked out.

p31
00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:45.127
Read the timeout column.

p32
00:01:45.861 --> 00:01:49.634
On the July eighth verified pass, cashiers get five minutes.

p33
00:01:49.854 --> 00:01:53.469
So do Managers, Senior Managers, and the entry-level roles.

p34
00:01:54.122 --> 00:01:57.952
Customer Service and the back-office levels get two full hours.

p35
00:01:58.446 --> 00:02:01.403
So a cashier dropping out mid-shift isn't a bug,

p36
00:02:01.691 --> 00:02:04.376
it's the level doing exactly what it was set to do.

p37
00:02:04.813 --> 00:02:08.147
Back under Users and Security, open Security Level.

p38
00:02:08.750 --> 00:02:13.689
The link says Security Level, the page says Security Levels, same destination.

p39
00:02:14.477 --> 00:02:18.821
Three columns: a name, a level number,

p40
00:02:19.105 --> 00:02:20.710
and the one support cares about, Refund Approval Required.

p41
00:02:21.231 --> 00:02:22.018
Here's the gate.

p42
00:02:22.490 --> 00:02:28.527
On the verified pass, levels zero, three, and five needed approval before a refund could go through.

p43
00:02:29.043 --> 00:02:30.589
Eight and above did not.

p44
00:02:31.228 --> 00:02:32.827
The rule underneath is plain: level five or below asks permission, eight or over just refunds.

p45
00:02:33.175 --> 00:02:40.547
One column settles most of these disputes.

p46
00:02:41.001 --> 00:02:44.381
Now tie the pages together.

p47
00:02:44.381 --> 00:02:46.828
A person's role sets their user level.

p48
00:02:46.828 --> 00:02:49.267
Their user level carries a security number.

p49
00:02:49.267 --> 00:02:52.661
That security number decides whether they can approve a refund.

p50
00:02:52.661 --> 00:02:56.006
So a manager who can't refund isn't being blocked at random,

p51
00:02:56.006 --> 00:02:59.046
their level maps to a security number that requires sign-off.

p52
00:02:59.046 --> 00:03:01.598
Trace it in that order every time.

p53
00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:02.925
Last page.

p54
00:03:03.317 --> 00:03:04.736
Open Blacklisted.

p55
00:03:05.437 --> 00:03:08.119
These are plates the system refuses at the wash.

p56
00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:14.931
Four columns: the plate itself, the terminal where the block was set, who added it, and when.

p57
00:03:15.389 --> 00:03:17.782
This page answers one specific call.

p58
00:03:18.260 --> 00:03:22.657
When a customer swears their plate won't scan, look here before anything else.

p59
00:03:23.511 --> 00:03:26.961
If the plate's on the list, you can see who blocked it and when,

p60
00:03:27.332 --> 00:03:29.760
which turns a mystery into a two-minute answer.

p61
00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:32.165
One rule covers all four pages.

p62
00:03:32.165 --> 00:03:37.184
Each has a New Record button, and an admin can edit every list.

p63
00:03:37.184 --> 00:03:38.803
You only read them.

p64
00:03:38.803 --> 00:03:42.478
Passwords, levels, and blocks are changed by an administrator in production,

p65
00:03:42.478 --> 00:03:44.483
never from a support seat.

p66
00:03:44.483 --> 00:03:49.062
And when the account uses single sign-on, a password reset here does nothing;

p67
00:03:49.062 --> 00:03:51.401
that fix lives with the identity provider.

p68
00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:54.434
So, four pages, four questions.

p69
00:03:54.903 --> 00:03:55.794
Can they sign in: System Users.

p70
00:03:56.145 --> 00:03:57.139
Why do they keep dropping: User Levels.

p71
00:03:58.217 --> 00:03:59.579
Why can't they refund: Security Levels.

p72
00:03:59.967 --> 00:04:00.912
Why won't the plate scan: Blacklisted.

p73
00:04:01.746 --> 00:04:12.477
Learn where each one lives, and half your access tickets start answering themselves.

